   =20
	<header class=3D"entry-header">
    	<h1 class=3D"entry-title">How Much Yardage Do I Need??</h1>
		<div class=3D"entry-meta">
			<span class=3D"posted-on">Posted on <a href=3D"https://historicalsewing.=
com/how-much-yardage-do-i-need" rel=3D"bookmark"><time class=3D"entry-date =
published" datetime=3D"2018-09-12T10:12:02-06:00">September 12, 2018</time>=
<time class=3D"updated" datetime=3D"2019-08-07T16:48:49-06:00">August 7, 20=
19</time></a></span><span class=3D"byline"> </span>		</div><!-- .entry-meta=
 -->
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->
   =20
            <div class=3D"entry-thumbnail"><img width=3D"682" height=3D"512=
" src=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/wp-content/uploads/How-Much-Yardage.j=
pg" class=3D"attachment-full size-full wp-post-image" alt=3D"How Much Yarda=
ge Do I Need?" decoding=3D"async"></div>
   =20
	<div class=3D"entry-content">
		<p><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter wp-image-5506 size-large"=
 title=3D"How Much Yardage Do I Need? " src=3D"https://historicalsewing.com=
/wp-content/uploads/How-Much-Yardage-485x364.jpg" alt=3D"How Much Yardage D=
o I Need? | HistoricalSewing.com" width=3D"485" height=3D"364"></p>
<p>We=E2=80=99ve all been there. Standing in an aisle of gorgeous fabrics=
=E2=80=A6 swooning at the computer screen=E2=80=A6 gazing lovingly (and wit=
h drool at the mouth) at THE.PERFECT.FABRIC for that next dress.</p>
<p>Question is=E2=80=A6 how much to buy??</p>
<p>Will 5 yards be enough? 10? Or do I have to sell a kidney to afford some=
 unmentionable amount of fibers woven together into a textile?? (=E2=80=9CT=
hink I=E2=80=99ll just get a yard and use for trim some time.=E2=80=9D hehe=
)</p>
<p><span id=3D"more-5493"></span></p>
<p>I=E2=80=99ve compiled a list of common garments from the 19<sup>th</sup>=
 Century and their approximate yardage requirements. Please note =E2=80=93 =
these are *approximate.*</p>
<p>You=E2=80=99ll have to adjust for larger or smaller material widths and =
for your size (i.e. a 4=E2=80=9911=E2=80=9D person will take less yardage t=
han my 5=E2=80=998=E2=80=B3 mother). Take a look at this <a title=3D"How to=
 Use a Fabric Conversion Chart" href=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/how-to=
-use-a-fabric-conversion-chart" rel=3D"noopener">conversion chart</a> for w=
hen you find that =E2=80=9Cmust have=E2=80=9D fabric.</p>
<p><strong>The yardages listed approximate using 45=E2=80=B3 fabric</strong=
>. If you find a to-die-for silk taffeta in 58=E2=80=B3 you might not need =
as much. Also, if you plan on creating self-trim =E2=80=93 you may need sev=
eral more yards. <a title=3D"How to Calculate Yardage for Ruffles" href=3D"=
https://historicalsewing.com/how-to-calculate-yardage-for-ruffles" rel=3D"n=
oopener">For ruffles use these calculations</a>. For <a title=3D"Techniques=
 for Easier Pleating in 19th Century Costuming" href=3D"https://historicals=
ewing.com/techniques-for-easier-pleating-in-19th-century-costuming" rel=3D"=
noopener">pleating read this article</a>.</p>
<p>These yardages assume cutting the garment pieces on the =E2=80=9Cnormal=
=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/tips-for-working-with-fab=
ric-grainlines">grain</a> for the era =E2=80=93 most often =E2=80=9Con=E2=
=80=9D grain for bodices and skirts and bias cut for sleeves.</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_5502" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-5502"=
 style=3D"width: 334px" class=3D"wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"wp-image-5502 size-large" title=3D"1813 Aft=
ernoon Promenade Dress" src=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/wp-content/uplo=
ads/1813-Afternoon-Promenade-Dress-334x600.jpg" alt=3D"1813 Afternoon Prome=
nade Dress" width=3D"334" height=3D"600"><figcaption id=3D"caption-attachme=
nt-5502" class=3D"wp-caption-text">1813 Afternoon Promenade Dress</figcapti=
on></figure>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style=3D"text-decoration: underline; color: #000000; font-size: 18=
px;"><b>Regency Era c.1800 to 1820</b></span></p>
<ul>
<li>Basic Dress =E2=80=93 5 to 7 yards</li>
<li>Evening/Ball Dress with train =E2=80=93 6 to 8 yards</li>
<li>Spencer jacket =E2=80=93 2 to 3 yards</li>
<li>Pelisse or Coat =E2=80=93 3.5 to 5 yards</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_5496" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-5496"=
 style=3D"width: 307px" class=3D"wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"wp-image-5496 size-large" title=3D"Jennifer=
 in 1830 fashion plate reproduction" src=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/wp=
-content/uploads/1830s-Green-Day-Dress-front-Copy-307x600.jpg" alt=3D"Jenni=
fer in 1830 fashion plate reproduction" width=3D"307" height=3D"600"><figca=
ption id=3D"caption-attachment-5496" class=3D"wp-caption-text">Jennifer in =
1830 fashion plate reproduction</figcaption></figure>
<p><span style=3D"text-decoration: underline; font-size: 18px;"><span style=
=3D"color: #000000;"><b>Romantic Era c.1820s &amp; 1830s</b></span></span><=
/p>
<ul>
<li>Bodice =E2=80=93 1 to 1.5 yards</li>
<li>Full puffed sleeves (short), pair =E2=80=93 1 to 1.25 yards</li>
<li>Full length leg o=E2=80=99 mutton sleeves, pair =E2=80=93 1.5 to 2 yard=
s</li>
<li>Skirt =E2=80=93 3.5 to 5 yards</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_5500" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-5500"=
 style=3D"width: 383px" class=3D"wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"wp-image-5500 size-large" title=3D"1846 Sep=
tember - Les Modes Parisiennes" src=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/wp-cont=
ent/uploads/1846-September-plate-green-and-white-gowns-383x600.jpg" alt=3D"=
1846 September - Les Modes Parisiennes" width=3D"383" height=3D"600"><figca=
ption id=3D"caption-attachment-5500" class=3D"wp-caption-text">1846 Septemb=
er =E2=80=93 Les Modes Parisiennes</figcaption></figure>
<p><span style=3D"text-decoration: underline;"><span style=3D"color: #00000=
0; font-size: 18px;"><b>Early Victorian c.1840s</b></span></span></p>
<ul>
<li>Bodice with long, tight bias-cut sleeves =E2=80=93 2.25 to 3 yards</li>
<li>Evening bodice with short sleeves =E2=80=93 1.75 to 2.5 yards</li>
<li>Skirt =E2=80=93 4 to 5.5 yards</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_5498" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-5498"=
 style=3D"width: 450px" class=3D"wp-caption aligncenter"><a href=3D"http://=
www.metmuseum.org/collections/search-the-collections/80006071?img=3D0" targ=
et=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D=
"async" class=3D"wp-image-5498 size-large" title=3D"1859 Gold Tiered Dress =
from the Met Museum" src=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/wp-content/uploads=
/1859-Gold-Tiered-Dress-450x600.jpg" alt=3D"1859 Gold Tiered Dress" width=
=3D"450" height=3D"600"></a><figcaption id=3D"caption-attachment-5498" clas=
s=3D"wp-caption-text">1859 Gold Tiered Dress from the Met Museum</figcaptio=
n></figure>
<p><span style=3D"text-decoration: underline; font-size: 18px;"><span style=
=3D"color: #000000;"><b>Mid-Victorian c.1850s &amp; 1860s</b></span></span>=
</p>
<ul>
<li>Bodice with pagoda sleeves =E2=80=93 3 to 4 yards</li>
<li>Bodice with fitted sleeves =E2=80=93 2 to 3 yards</li>
<li>Evening/Ball gown bodice =E2=80=93 1.5 to 2 yards</li>
<li>Skirt, plain =E2=80=93 5 to 6.5 yards</li>
<li>Skirt with 3 deep ruffles =E2=80=93 above plus 7 yards</li>
<li>Sheer dress =E2=80=93 8 to 10 yards</li>
</ul>
<p>To determine the ruffle yardage more accurately, <a title=3D"How to Calc=
ulate Yardage for Ruffles" href=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/how-to-calc=
ulate-yardage-for-ruffles" rel=3D"noopener">use this precise calculation</a=
>.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_5497" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-5497"=
 style=3D"width: 300px" class=3D"wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"wp-image-5497 size-large" title=3D"1885 Sil=
k Taffeta Dress from LACMA" src=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/wp-content/=
uploads/452A1-300x600.jpg" alt=3D"1885 Silk Taffeta Dress from LACMA" width=
=3D"300" height=3D"600"><figcaption id=3D"caption-attachment-5497" class=3D=
"wp-caption-text">1885 Silk Taffeta Dress from LACMA</figcaption></figure>
<p><span style=3D"text-decoration: underline; font-size: 18px;"><span style=
=3D"color: #000000;"><b>Bustle Era c.1870 to 1889</b></span></span></p>
<ul>
<li>Basic bodice =E2=80=93 2.5 to 4 yards depending on the length down on t=
he hips</li>
<li>Apron overskirt =E2=80=93 3 to 6 yards</li>
<li>Foundation/Underskirt =E2=80=93 4 to 5.5 yards</li>
<li>Foundation skirt with train =E2=80=93 5 to 8 yards</li>
</ul>
<p>Eight to 12 yards is a good starting point for bustle dresses.</p>
<p>The Bustle years are <a title=3D"Bustle Era Changes =E2=80=93 The Highs =
&amp; Lows in the 1870s &amp; 1880s" href=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/b=
ustle-era-changes-the-highs-lows-in-the-1870s-1880s" rel=3D"noopener">quite=
 varied</a> and can greatly affect amount of yardage needed. (How foofy do =
you want it?)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_5501" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-5501"=
 style=3D"width: 423px" class=3D"wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"wp-image-5501 size-large" title=3D"1896 Apr=
il, The Delineator " src=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/wp-content/uploads=
/1896-April-Delineator-sm-423x600.jpg" alt=3D"1896 April, The Delineator " =
width=3D"423" height=3D"600"><figcaption id=3D"caption-attachment-5501" cla=
ss=3D"wp-caption-text">1896 April, The Delineator</figcaption></figure>
<p><span style=3D"text-decoration: underline; font-size: 18px;"><span style=
=3D"color: #000000;"><b>Late Victorian c.1890s</b></span></span></p>
<ul>
<li>Bodice (only) =E2=80=93 1.5 to 2.5 yards</li>
<li>Full length leg o=E2=80=99 mutton sleeves, pair =E2=80=93 1.5 to 3 yard=
s</li>
<li>Short puffed sleeves, pair =E2=80=93 1.5 to 2.5 yards</li>
<li>Skirt =E2=80=93 5 to 6.5 yards</li>
</ul>
<p><a href=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/sleeve-shifts-of-the-1890s">The =
1890s saw a wide variety of sleeve sizes</a>. Keep this in mind as you sele=
ct your particular costume year and how this can vary greatly as to the yar=
dage needed.<br>
For <a href=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/linings-underlinings-do-you-rea=
lly-need-both">underlining</a> fabrics, follow the same approximate yardage=
 as listed.</p>
<p>For fabric suppliers, check out the <a href=3D"https://historicalsewing.=
com/resources/fabrics-trims" rel=3D"noopener">Fabric &amp; Trim</a> Resourc=
e page.</p>
<p>Remember, it=E2=80=99s a good rule to ALWAYS buy a little bit more than =
you think you need. If you are matching plaids or stripes, cutting pieces o=
n the bias, this will take more yardage.</p>
<p>Self-trims (trims, ruffles, puffs, etc. cut from the dress or complement=
ary fabric) always take more than you think. Plan accordingly. Then <a href=
=3D"https://historicalsewing.com/small-yardages-in-the-stash">use these ide=
as for using up any small amounts</a> you=E2=80=99re left with.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Hope these guidelines help you! Let me know if I should add somethin=
g or can help you further.&nbsp;</em></p>
